  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some cultural faux pas in Hungary?",
  "response": "When visiting Hungary, it's helpful to be aware of certain cultural norms and practices to avoid potentially offending locals. Here are some common cultural faux pas to watch out for:\n\n1. **Handshake and Eye Contact:** When greeting someone, a firm handshake with direct eye contact is considered respectful. Avoid a limp handshake, as it can be seen as a sign of weakness or disinterest.\n\n2. **Politeness and Formality:** Address people with their titles and surnames until invited to use their first name. Using first names too soon can be seen as disrespectful.\n\n3. **Punctuality:** Being on time is important in Hungary, especially in business settings. Arriving late can be considered rude and disrespectful.\n\n4. **Shoes Indoors:** It is customary to take off your shoes when entering someone's home. Some hosts may offer you slippers to wear instead.\n\n5. **Cheers and Toasting:** When toasting, it's important to make eye contact with each person and say \u201cEg\u00e9szs\u00e9gedre!\u201d (To your health!). Avoid clinking glasses with beer, as this has historical connotations and might be frowned upon in some circles.\n\n6. **Personal Space:** Maintain an appropriate amount of personal space. Hugging is generally reserved for close friends and family members.\n\n7. **Gifts:** If bringing gifts to someone's home, opt for flowers, chocolates, or good quality wine. Avoid giving flowers in odd numbers, as even numbers are associated with funerals.\n\n8. **No Whistling Indoors:** Whistling indoors is considered bad luck and should be avoided.\n\n9. **Counting with Fingers:** When counting on your fingers, start with the thumb instead of the index finger.\n\n10. **Political and Historical Sensitivities:** Be mindful when discussing political or historical topics, especially those related to Hungary\u2019s past, as these subjects can be sensitive for many Hungarians.\n\nIt's always a good idea to approach interactions with an open mind and a respectful attitude to navigate cultural differences smoothly.",
